<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         xsi:schemaLocation="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0 https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd">
  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>

  <!--
    Chapter 30 companion (The Vulnerabilities You Write Yourself). Three Java vulnerability classes,
    each shown as a vulnerable shape beside the construction that designs it out: SQL injection
    (string concatenation versus a PreparedStatement bind parameter), insecure deserialization
    (readObject over request bytes versus a parsed fixed-shape record, with an ObjectInputFilter
    allow-list as the mitigation when native serialization is unavoidable), and cryptographic-API
    misuse (ECB + a Random IV + MD5 versus AES/GCM + SecureRandom + salted PBKDF2). The vulnerable
    types are deliberate teaching counter-examples, exercised only for behavior by a test and never
    wired into a running path; the SecurityGate running path uses the fixes alone. Crypto is JDK
    javax.crypto only. Runtime dependencies are JDK-only; the one extra GAV is the SpotBugs annotations
    artifact, on the compile path only.

    The module dogfoods the book: every shape is held to the same `quality` gate the chapter
    describes. The string-concatenated query is the one deliberate finding core SpotBugs raises at this
    threshold (SQL_NONCONSTANT_STRING_PASSED_TO_EXECUTE); it carries a single narrow, reasoned
    suppression in config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml. Detecting the crypto and deserialization
    misuse PATTERNS is a security analyzer's job (FindSecBugs, the SpotBugs security plugin) — see the
    README for why those are demonstrated by tests and prose here rather than by the core engine.
  -->
  <parent>
    <groupId>org.acme.storefront</groupId>
    <artifactId>companion-code</artifactId>
    <version>1.0.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
  </parent>

  <artifactId>secure-coding-owasp</artifactId>
  <name>Chapter 30 — The Vulnerabilities You Write Yourself (secure-coding-owasp)</name>

  <dependencies>
    <!--
      SpotBugs annotations (SOURCE-PIN.md: SpotBugs 4.10.2 line; this module builds against the locally
      cached 4.9.3 engine the companion code is pinned to, so the annotations track that engine). The
      single version literal here is the one pinned GAV available for a per-site
      @SuppressFBWarnings(value, justification) — not a BOM or version-set. The annotations are
      CLASS-retained, so `provided` scope keeps them on the compile path only and the module's runtime
      stays JDK-only like the rest of the companion code.
    -->
    <dependency>
      <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
      <artifactId>spotbugs-annotations</artifactId>
      <version>4.9.3</version>
      <scope>provided</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.junit.jupiter</groupId>
      <artifactId>junit-jupiter</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.assertj</groupId>
      <artifactId>assertj-core</artifactId>
      <scope>test</scope>
    </dependency>
  </dependencies>

  <!--
    Static-analysis rule gates from Chapter 16, opt-in via `-Pquality` so the default build stays
    fast. The maven-checkstyle-plugin ships an OLD bundled engine (Checkstyle 9.3); we override it to
    the pinned engine via a plugin-level dependency — the "two-pin" lesson (the build plugin and the
    analyzer engine are separate versions). This module is a direct child of the companion-code root,
    which pins no quality profile of its own, so the profile is declared here (the same shape the
    Chapter 09 and Chapter 26 modules use) and reads the config under this module's config/ dir.
  -->
  <profiles>
    <profile>
      <id>quality</id>
      <build>
        <plugins>
          <plugin>
            <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
            <artifactId>maven-checkstyle-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>3.6.0</version>
            <dependencies>
              <dependency>
                <groupId>com.puppycrawl.tools</groupId>
                <artifactId>checkstyle</artifactId>
                <version>10.26.1</version>
              </dependency>
            </dependencies>
            <configuration>
              <configLocation>config/checkstyle/checkstyle.xml</configLocation>
              <consoleOutput>true</consoleOutput>
              <failOnViolation>true</failOnViolation>
              <violationSeverity>error</violationSeverity>
              <includeTestSourceDirectory>true</includeTestSourceDirectory>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>checkstyle-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
          <!--
            SpotBugs: the bytecode vantage point (Chapter 16) — complementary to Checkstyle's source
            view. This module ships deliberate counter-examples; the string-concatenated query is the
            one core SpotBugs raises at this threshold and it carries a single narrowly-scoped,
            reasoned suppression in the exclude filter — the chapter's "suppress with a documented
            reason, never disable a detector" discipline, not a way to hide a real defect. The crypto
            and deserialization misuse patterns are FindSecBugs territory (not in this build's engine),
            so they are demonstrated by tests and prose rather than by the core detector.
          -->
          <plugin>
            <groupId>com.github.spotbugs</groupId>
            <artifactId>spotbugs-maven-plugin</artifactId>
            <version>4.9.3.0</version>
            <configuration>
              <effort>Max</effort>
              <threshold>Medium</threshold>
              <includeTests>false</includeTests>
              <excludeFilterFile>config/spotbugs/spotbugs-exclude.xml</excludeFilterFile>
            </configuration>
            <executions>
              <execution>
                <id>spotbugs-check</id>
                <phase>verify</phase>
                <goals>
                  <goal>check</goal>
                </goals>
              </execution>
            </executions>
          </plugin>
        </plugins>
      </build>
    </profile>
  </profiles>
</project>
